Subject: video: add quality=4 and forced_idr=1 to VAAPI encoder common options

Two encoder-side knobs Apollo wasn't setting, both relevant to Wi-Fi
streaming smoothness and packet-loss recovery:

1. `forced_idr=1` — when moonlight requests a mid-stream IDR frame
   (used for fast packet-loss recovery on Wi-Fi), ffmpeg's vaapi
   encoder may silently merge the IDR request into the next P-frame
   instead of emitting a real keyframe. With `forced_idr=1`, the IDR
   request always produces an actual IDR — moonlight's recovery path
   works as intended. Without it, after a packet loss the client may
   stay in a "waiting for keyframe" state for an extra GOP-length,
   which the user perceives as a stutter/freeze.

2. `quality=4` — AMD radeonsi VAAPI exposes a 0-8 quality preset
   (0 = speed-priority, 8 = quality-priority). 4 is a balanced
   low-latency point for RDNA encoders. Intel ignores this option.
   Without setting it, ffmpeg passes through whatever the underlying
   VA driver defaults to, which on RDNA3/4 is typically the
   quality-priority extreme — slower encode, more host CPU.

Both options are added to the "Common options" block for all three
VAAPI encoder profiles (av1_vaapi, hevc_vaapi, h264_vaapi). They are
inert on hardware that doesn't recognise them.

Combined with patch 0013 (VBR rate control on AMD), the user should
see noticeably smoother streaming and faster recovery from any Wi-Fi
hiccups.

--- a/src/video.cpp
+++ b/src/video.cpp
@@ -925,6 +925,14 @@
       {
         {"async_depth"s, 1},
         {"idr_interval"s, std::numeric_limits<int>::max()},
+        // forced_idr=1 so moonlight's mid-stream IDR requests
+        // (for packet-loss recovery on Wi-Fi) are honoured as real
+        // IDR frames instead of being merged into P frames.
+        {"forced_idr"s, 1},
+        // quality knob on AMD radeonsi VAAPI: lower = faster encode,
+        // higher = better quality. 4 is a balanced low-latency point
+        // for AMD RDNA encoders (Intel ignores this option).
+        {"quality"s, 4},
       },
       {},  // SDR-specific options
       {},  // HDR-specific options
@@ -939,6 +947,8 @@
         {"async_depth"s, 1},
         {"sei"s, 0},
         {"idr_interval"s, std::numeric_limits<int>::max()},
+        {"forced_idr"s, 1},
+        {"quality"s, 4},
       },
       {},  // SDR-specific options
       {},  // HDR-specific options
@@ -953,6 +963,8 @@
         {"async_depth"s, 1},
         {"sei"s, 0},
         {"idr_interval"s, std::numeric_limits<int>::max()},
+        {"forced_idr"s, 1},
+        {"quality"s, 4},
       },
       {},  // SDR-specific options
       {},  // HDR-specific options
